<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[163,779,663,1083]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicName box="[163,533,663,684]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karakalense">
<emphasis box="[163,533,663,684]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Pseudoanthidium karakalense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from Kara-Kala in 
<collectingCountry box="[353,540,693,715]" name="Turkmenistan" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Turkmenistan</collectingCountry>
. Popov described 
<taxonomicName box="[163,330,724,746]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karakalense">
<emphasis box="[163,330,724,746]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. karakalense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dusmet y Alsonso" authorityYear="1915" box="[494,625,724,746]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Anthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astilleroi">
<emphasis box="[494,625,724,746]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. astilleroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but with the female differing in certain morphological characters, including the punctation on the frons, the straight edge of the clypeal margin, the length of the first, second and third antennal segments and the paler yellow colour. He further noted that this taxon differed from 
<taxonomicName box="[227,373,908,930]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Zygophyllaceae" genus="Pseuodanthidium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygophyllales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lituratum">
<emphasis box="[227,373,908,930]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. lituratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its punctation, size, coloration and male genitalia. A careful examination of Popovâ€™s 
<typeStatus box="[163,214,970,991]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">type</typeStatus>
material confirms the synonymy of this taxon with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dours" baseAuthorityYear="1873" box="[227,421,1001,1022]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stigmaticorne">
<emphasis box="[227,421,1001,1022]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. stigmaticorne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Warncke K" box="[437,627,1000,1022]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="119 - 210" refId="ref36293" refString="Warncke K. 1980. Die Bienengattung Anthidium Fabricius, 1804 in der Westpalaarktis und im turkestanischen Becken. Entomofauna 1: 119 - 210." type="journal article" year="1980">Warncke (1980)</bibRefCitation>
erroneously placed this taxon in synonymy with 
<taxonomicName box="[591,737,1031,1052]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cribratum">
<emphasis box="[591,737,1031,1052]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. cribratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Morawitz" authorityYear="1875" box="[163,527,1061,1082]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Anthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="lituratum" subSpecies="cribratum">
<emphasis box="[163,527,1061,1082]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Anthidium lituratum cribratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[163,779,1124,1575]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis box="[163,364,1124,1146]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Diagnosis female:</emphasis>
The female of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dours" baseAuthorityYear="1873" box="[543,723,1125,1146]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stigmaticorne">
<emphasis box="[543,723,1125,1146]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. stigmaticorne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be distinguished from other members of this complex by the following combination of characters: punctation on terga comparatively coarse, as large or larger than punctation on mesonotum and with shiny interspaces between punctures; largest punctures on black part of scutellum smaller in diameter than largest punctures on T2; punctation on vertex between lateral ocellus, eye and postoccipital margin small but distinct, with shiny narrow spaces between most punctures; clypeus either yellow, yellow with black markings or black; small, mostly less than 
<quantity box="[453,543,1461,1483]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[561,728,1461,1483]" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="23.[164,244,1201,1223]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1161]" captionTargetId="figure-344@23.[323,1283,195,1161]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="Figure 17. Dorsal habitus, females. A, vertex Pseudoanthidium stigmaticorne (Arzens, France); B, vertex P. cribratum (Bukhara, Uzbekistan); C, mesonotum P.stigmaticorne (Arzens, France); D, mesonotum P.cribratum (Bukhara, Uzbekistan); E, metasoma P. stigmaticorne (Arzens, France); F, metasoma P. cribratum (Bukhara, Uzbekistan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817312" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817312/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 17A, C, E</figureCitation>
). In their zone of overlap (e.g. in 
<collectingRegion box="[499,588,1492,1514]" country="Ukraine" name="Crimea" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Crimea</collectingRegion>
), differentiating females of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dours" baseAuthorityYear="1873" box="[290,477,1523,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stigmaticorne">
<emphasis box="[290,477,1523,1544]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. stigmaticorne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mocsary" authorityYear="1879" box="[649,779,1522,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Anthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenellum">
<emphasis box="[649,779,1522,1544]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. tenellum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be challenging in some cases.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[163,779,1616,1883]" lastBlockId="25.[827,1444,197,740]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis box="[163,347,1616,1637]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Diagnosis male:</emphasis>
The male of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dours" baseAuthorityYear="1873" box="[504,688,1616,1638]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stigmaticorne">
<emphasis box="[504,688,1616,1638]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. stigmaticorne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be distinguished from other members of this complex by the following combination of characters: gonostylus approximately 1.5 times wider at widest point than at base (
<figureCitation box="[267,398,1738,1760]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="24.[145,224,1340,1362]" captionTargetBox="[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetId="figure-257@24.[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Figure 18. Gonostyli, Pseudoanthidium stigmaticorne. A, Cape Lukull, Crimea; B, Bet Sheâ€™an, Israel; C, Agadir, Morocco; D, RestincliÃ¨res, France; E, Cacela Velha, Portugal; F, Seui, Sardinia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817314" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817314/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 18Aâ€“F</figureCitation>
); exterior margin of gonostylus relatively straight, inner margin more sharply rounded toward apex (
<figureCitation box="[319,445,1800,1822]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="24.[145,224,1340,1362]" captionTargetBox="[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetId="figure-257@24.[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Figure 18. Gonostyli, Pseudoanthidium stigmaticorne. A, Cape Lukull, Crimea; B, Bet Sheâ€™an, Israel; C, Agadir, Morocco; D, RestincliÃ¨res, France; E, Cacela Velha, Portugal; F, Seui, Sardinia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817314" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817314/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 18Aâ€“F</figureCitation>
); notch at apex of gonostylus either as deep as opening of notch is wide and more or less centred at apex of gonostylus (most European and Central Asian populations) or notch significantly less deep than opening of notch is wide and strongly offset laterally (northern Africa, southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1303,1358,258,280]" name="Italy" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Italy</collectingCountry>
) (notch deeper in other species) (
<figureCitation box="[1116,1242,289,311]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="24.[145,224,1340,1362]" captionTargetBox="[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetId="figure-257@24.[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Figure 18. Gonostyli, Pseudoanthidium stigmaticorne. A, Cape Lukull, Crimea; B, Bet Sheâ€™an, Israel; C, Agadir, Morocco; D, RestincliÃ¨res, France; E, Cacela Velha, Portugal; F, Seui, Sardinia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817314" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817314/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 18Aâ€“F</figureCitation>
); lateral comb on S5 small, with longest teeth shorter than maximal width of hind basitarsus (comb larger in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1809" box="[1299,1437,350,372]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Anthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scapulare">
<emphasis box="[1299,1437,350,372]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. scapulare</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[827,936,382,403]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanum">
<emphasis box="[827,936,382,403]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. nanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mocsary" authorityYear="1879" box="[949,1076,381,403]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Anthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenellum">
<emphasis box="[949,1076,381,403]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. tenellum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1134,1309,381,403]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palestinicum">
<emphasis box="[1134,1309,381,403]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. palestinicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation box="[1333,1429,381,403]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="17.[164,243,1501,1523]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-186@17.[323,1283,195,1461]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figure 11. Sternal combs. A, Pseudoanthidium nanum (Dordogne, France); B, P. scapulare (ArgÃ¨les-sur-Mer, France); C, P. stigmaticorne (Cabanes de Fleury, France); D, P. tenellum (Krasnoperekopsk, Crimea); E, P. palestinicum (Jerusalem, Israel); F, P. cribratum (Ayelet Hashar, Israel); G, P. kaspareki (Side, Turkey); H, P. rozeni (Hanna, Pakistan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817300/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 11C</figureCitation>
); comb of S5 no wider than arm preceding it (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="17.[164,243,1501,1523]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-186@17.[323,1283,195,1461]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figure 11. Sternal combs. A, Pseudoanthidium nanum (Dordogne, France); B, P. scapulare (ArgÃ¨les-sur-Mer, France); C, P. stigmaticorne (Cabanes de Fleury, France); D, P. tenellum (Krasnoperekopsk, Crimea); E, P. palestinicum (Jerusalem, Israel); F, P. cribratum (Ayelet Hashar, Israel); G, P. kaspareki (Side, Turkey); H, P. rozeni (Hanna, Pakistan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817300/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 11C</figureCitation>
); posterior, premarginal brush on S3 with hairs hooked at tips (hairs unhooked in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mocsary" authorityYear="1879" box="[1253,1388,473,495]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Anthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenellum">
<emphasis box="[1253,1388,473,495]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. tenellum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[827,967,504,525]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Pseudoanthidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cribratum">
<emphasis box="[827,967,504,525]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">P. cribratum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and arranged in an open brushy arc (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="18.[146,227,1493,1515]" captionTargetBox="[305,1265,195,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-192@18.[305,1265,195,1453]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 12. S3, males. A, Pseudoanthidium nanum (Dordogne, France); B, P. scapulare (ArgÃ¨les-sur-Mer, France); C, P. stigmaticorne (Cabanes de Fleury, France); D, P. tenellum (Krasnoperekopsk, Crimea); E, P. palestinicum (Jerusalem, Israel); F, P. cribratum (Ayelet Hashar, Israel); G, P. kaspareki (Side, Turkey); H, P. rozeni (Hanna, Pakistan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817302" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817302/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 12C</figureCitation>
); no shiny, hairless zone on S3 between posterior premarginal brush of hairs and anterior zone of dense, velvety pilosity (present in other species) (
<figureCitation box="[1329,1428,596,618]" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="18.[146,227,1493,1515]" captionTargetBox="[305,1265,195,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-192@18.[305,1265,195,1453]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 12. S3, males. A, Pseudoanthidium nanum (Dordogne, France); B, P. scapulare (ArgÃ¨les-sur-Mer, France); C, P. stigmaticorne (Cabanes de Fleury, France); D, P. tenellum (Krasnoperekopsk, Crimea); E, P. palestinicum (Jerusalem, Israel); F, P. cribratum (Ayelet Hashar, Israel); G, P. kaspareki (Side, Turkey); H, P. rozeni (Hanna, Pakistan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817302" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817302/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 12C</figureCitation>
); darkened raised zone across S2 with only short, sparse hairs, in shape of â€˜moustacheâ€™ (
<figureCitation box="[1213,1315,657,679]" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="19.[163,244,1498,1520]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1458]" captionTargetId="figure-171@19.[323,1283,195,1458]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figure 13. S2, males. A, Pseudoanthidium nanum (Dordogne, France); B, P. scapulare (ArgÃ¨les-sur-Mer, France); C, P. stigmaticorne (Cabanes de Fleury, France); D, P. tenellum (Krasnoperekopsk, Crimea); E, P. palestinicum (Jerusalem, Israel); F, P. cribratum (Ayelet Hashar, Israel); G, P. kaspareki (Side, Turkey); H, P. rozeni (Hanna, Pakistan)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817304" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817304/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 13C</figureCitation>
); hairs on ventral surface of trochanter 3 shaggy and uneven, not dense, with longer hairs toward base.
</paragraph>
