<paragraph blockId="26.[145,761,1021,1902]" lastBlockId="26.[809,1425,1021,1166]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
The colour patterns seen in males are mostly similar to those in females from the same regions except that the clypeus in males is typically pale, creamy yellow. In some populations, such as those in Crimea, pale yellow maculations on metasoma are present on T1â€“ T4, T5â€“T6 are entirely black and T7 is pale yellow. In the Middle East, paired maculations are present on T1â€“T6 and T7 is yellow or, alternatively, paired maculations are present on T1â€“T5, T6 is black and T7 is pale yellow. We have also examined specimens from Dagestan in which lemon-yellow maculations are present on T1â€“T5, T6 is black and T7 is pale yellow. Specimens from northern Africa are similar to those in Dagestan but the posterior margin of T6 is yellow. In individuals from 
<collectingCountry box="[464,545,1666,1687]" name="France" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">France</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[605,674,1665,1687]" name="Spain" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Spain</collectingCountry>
, paired maculations are present on T1â€“T6 and T7 is yellow, although this varies considerably. The notch at the apex of the gonostylus is approximately as deep as the opening of the notch is wide and more or less centred at apex of gonostylus in most individuals. However, in Middle Eastern populations the gonostylus is more flared at the apex (
<figureCitation box="[369,466,1880,1902]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="24.[145,224,1340,1362]" captionTargetBox="[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetId="figure-257@24.[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Figure 18. Gonostyli, Pseudoanthidium stigmaticorne. A, Cape Lukull, Crimea; B, Bet Sheâ€™an, Israel; C, Agadir, Morocco; D, RestincliÃ¨res, France; E, Cacela Velha, Portugal; F, Seui, Sardinia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817314" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817314/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 18B</figureCitation>
) and in northern African populations the gonostylus is strongly flared at the apex and the notch is much less deep than it is wide at the opening (
<figureCitation box="[992,1088,1082,1104]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="24.[145,224,1340,1362]" captionTargetBox="[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetId="figure-257@24.[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Figure 18. Gonostyli, Pseudoanthidium stigmaticorne. A, Cape Lukull, Crimea; B, Bet Sheâ€™an, Israel; C, Agadir, Morocco; D, RestincliÃ¨res, France; E, Cacela Velha, Portugal; F, Seui, Sardinia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817314" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817314/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 18C</figureCitation>
). Specimens with a similarly shaped gonostylus are also occasionally observed in other regions (
<figureCitation box="[974,1070,1144,1166]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="24.[145,224,1340,1362]" captionTargetBox="[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetId="figure-257@24.[225,1345,195,1301]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Figure 18. Gonostyli, Pseudoanthidium stigmaticorne. A, Cape Lukull, Crimea; B, Bet Sheâ€™an, Israel; C, Agadir, Morocco; D, RestincliÃ¨res, France; E, Cacela Velha, Portugal; F, Seui, Sardinia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5817314" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5817314/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 18D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
